'''Jorge Artur Rego de Brito''' <small>[[Order of Prince Henry|ComIH]] [[Order of Merit (Portugal)|ComM]]</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ordens.presidencia.pt/?idc=153|title=Cidadãos nacionais agraciados com Ordens Portuguesas|website=Presidency of the Portuguese Republic|language=Portuguese|trans-title=National citizens decorated with Portuguese Orders|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> (7 November 1927 – 2 August 2006) was a Portuguese businessman, founder of Banco Intercontinental Português (BIP) and [[Brisa – Auto-estradas de Portugal|Brisa]],<ref name="empresário"/> who served as the [[List of S.L. Benfica presidents|28th president]] of sports club [[S.L. Benfica]], succeeding João Santos.

During Brito's term at Benfica, from 24 April 1992 to 7 January 1994, its [[association football|football team]] won the [[1993 Taça de Portugal Final|Taça de Portugal in 1993]]. At the end of that year, during the [[1993–94 S.L. Benfica season|following season]], he resigned due to financial difficulties<ref name="benfica">{{cite web|url=https://www.slbenfica.pt/pt-pt/slb/historia/presidentes/|title=Presidentes: os nomes que marcam a história|date=15 March 2018|website=S.L. Benfica|language=Portuguese|trans-title=Presidents: the names that mark the history|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> dating back to "Verão Quente" (Hot Summer), when Benfica did not sign new players and lost two players to [[Lisbon]] rivals [[Sporting CP|Sporting]],<ref>{{cite news|date=3 August 2006|title=Benfica: plantel e muitas figuras do futebol no último adeus a Jorge de Brito|trans-title=Benfica: the team and many football figures in a last farewell to Jorge de Brito|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/benfica/iol/712937-1456.html|language=Portuguese|work=Maisfutebol|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> thus not completing his triennal term. He was succeeded by [[Manuel Damásio]].<ref name="benfica"/>

Associate number 88, Brito was awarded with the Águia de Ouro (Golden Eagle) by Benfica on 14 December 1973, during the presidency of [[Duarte Borges Coutinho]]. Brito died in Lisbon, aged 78, after a long illness, and was buried at [[Prazeres Cemetery]].<ref name="empresário"/><ref>{{cite news|date=2 August 2006|title=Faleceu Jorge de Brito|trans-title=Jorge de Brito has died|url=http://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/faleceu-jorge-de-brito.html|language=Portuguese|newspaper=Record|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref>

