'''Valleyspeak''' or '''Valspeak''' is an American [[sociolect]], originally of the [[San Fernando Valley]] in [[Southern California]]. This sociolect became an international fad for a certain period in the 1980s and 1990s, with a peak period from around 1981 to 1985. Many phrases and elements of Valleyspeak, along with [[Surf culture|surfer slang]] and [[skateboarding]] [[slang]], have become staple elements of the [[California English]] dialect lexicon, and in some cases wider [[American English]] (such as the widespread use of "like" as a [[discourse marker]]).
==Origin== The term "Valley Girl" and the Valley manner of speech was given a wider circulation with the release of a hit 1982 single by [[Frank Zappa]] titled "[[Valley Girl (song)|Valley Girl]]", on which [[Moon Zappa]], Frank's then fourteen-year-old daughter, delivered a monologue in "Valleyspeak" behind the music. This song popularized phrases such as "[[wikt:grody|grody]] to the max" and "[[wikt:gag me with a spoon|gag me with a spoon]]".
An early appearance of Valleyspeak and the Valley Girl stereotype was through the character of Jennifer DiNuccio, played by [[Tracy Nelson (actress)|Tracy Nelson]] in the 1982–1983 [[sitcom]] ''[[Square Pegs]]''. According to an interview with Nelson included on the 2008 [[DVD]] release of the series, she developed the character's Valleyspeak and personality prior to the Zappa recording becoming popular.<ref>"Weemawee Yearbook Memories: Tracy Nelson and Claudette Wells", a featurette on the DVD release ''Square Pegs: The Like, Totally Complete Series&nbsp;... Totally'' (Sony Pictures Home Entertainment, 2008).</ref>
Among the recognizable characters with Valley Girl accents are Hillary Banks (Fresh Prince of Bel Air,) Cher Horowitz of ''[[Clueless (film)|Clueless]]'' and [[Cassandra Peterson|Elvira, Mistress of the Dark]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}
== Features == * [[High rising terminal]] (also called "up speak" or "uptalk") is a defining feature of Valleyspeak. Statements have a rising intonation, causing declarative language to appear interrogative to listeners unfamiliar with the dialect. Research on uptalk has found a number of [[Pragmatics|pragmatic]] uses, including confirming that the interlocutor follows what is being said and indicating that the speaker has more to say and so their conversation partner should not interrupt them (also called "floor holding").<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://well.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/12/23/overturning-the-myth-of-valley-girl-speak/|title=Overturning the Myth of Valley Girl Speak|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|date=2013-12-23|website=Well|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> The high rising terminal feature has been adopted by speakers beyond the traditional users of Valleyspeak, including men<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-25232387|title=More men speaking in girls' 'dialect', study shows|last=Hogenboom|first=Melissa|date=2013-12-06|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/is-valley-girl-speak--like--on-the-rise-/|title=Is Valley Girl Speak, Like, on the Rise?|date=2013-12-07|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref> and New Zealanders<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/200511/valley-girl-talk|title=Valley Girl Talk|website=Psychology Today|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>. * "[[Like]]" as a [[discourse marker]], often used as an approximative adverb. * "To be like" as a [[Colloquialism|colloquial]] [[quotative]]. "Like" (always unstressed) is used to indicate that what follows is not necessarily an exact quotation of what was said, but captures the meaning and intention of the quoted speech. As an example, in "And I was like, 'don't ever speak to my boyfriend again'", the speaker is indicating that they may or may not have literally said those words, but they conveyed that idea.{{cn|date=May 2018}}
